5	3	8	\N	\N	\N	821	en	[]	[{"answer": "I built a real-time collaboration feature for a document editor using WebSockets and operational transforms to handle concurrent edits. The main challenge was conflict resolution when two users edited the same paragraph simultaneously. I implemented a last-writer-wins fallback with visual conflict indicators for the user.", "question": "Describe the most technically challenging project you have worked on."}, {"answer": "I start by identifying the read versus write ratio since that drives most architectural decisions. For read-heavy systems I lean on CDN caching, database read replicas, and denormalization. For write-heavy I look at event sourcing and message queues. I also design for horizontal scaling from the start rather than adding it later.", "question": "How do you approach designing a system that needs to scale to millions of users?"}, {"answer": "We needed to ship a search feature fast. I chose Elasticsearch over building a custom solution even though it added operational complexity. The trade-off was faster delivery and better search quality versus learning curve and infra cost. I documented the decision with an ADR so the team understood the reasoning.", "question": "Tell me about a time you had to make a difficult technical trade-off."}, {"answer": "I first assume the reviewer knows something I do not and re-read their comment carefully. If I still disagree I write a clear explanation of my reasoning and invite discussion. I have changed my mind about 60 percent of the time after that conversation and held my ground the other 40 with good justification.", "question": "How do you handle code review feedback you disagree with?"}, {"answer": "I want to move from being strong in frontend to being a well-rounded engineer who can own full features end to end. I am actively learning distributed systems and want to lead technical design for at least one major feature within the next year.", "question": "Where do you see yourself technically in three years?"}]	9.0	8.0	8.0	8.0	8.2	Nadia demonstrated strong technical awareness with concrete examples (e.g., WebSockets for real-time collaboration) and clear trade-off analysis. Her communication was precise but could be more concise in Q4. Technical depth is solid but lacks depth in distributed systems. Confidence was high with specific evidence (e.g., 60% change in code review decisions). CultureFit shows proactive learning and collaboration.	Consider - Nadia shows strong technical fundamentals and clear decision-making, but her distributed systems knowledge is slightly underdeveloped for senior roles. Her code review approach is a standout strength.	[{"index": 1, "score": 9, "feedback": "Specific technical example with clear problem-solution (WebSockets, conflict resolution) shows strong practical understanding."}, {"index": 2, "score": 8, "feedback": "Good understanding of scaling strategies but could elaborate more on how read/write ratios impact real-world systems (e.g., latency, cost)."}, {"index": 3, "score": 9, "feedback": "Clear trade-off with measurable outcome (60% change in decisions) and documentation (ADR) shows strong decision-making."}, {"index": 4, "score": 8, "feedback": "Good process for handling disagreements but could be more concise in explaining the 60/40 split without overcomplicating the narrative."}, {"index": 5, "score": 8, "feedback": "Realistic and actionable goals (distributed systems, end-to-end ownership) but lacks specific technical milestones for the next year."}]	2026-06-08 06:04:31.180375+00		[]
